Plants have sex? Yes, they totally do.<br />
<br />
<b>A brief overview:&nbsp;</b><br />
Plants have female reproductive organs (carpels) and male reproductive organs (stamens), but several different ways of determining sex. There are two main groups of seed-producing plants.<br />
<br />
<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gymnosperm" target="_blank">Gymnosperms</a>&nbsp;are plants without covered seeds, and include those that produce cones. Gymnosperms and are split with about 75% exhibiting <a href="http://www.thefreedictionary.com/monoecy" target="_blank">monoecy</a> (having male and female sex organs on the same plant), and 25% exhibiting <a href="http://www.thefreedictionary.com/dioecy" target="_blank">dioecy</a> (having separate male plants and female plants).<br />
